# First Java Program

```java
public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        System.out.println("Hello, World!");

    }

}
```

---

# Java Program Structure

A Java program consists of:

- Class
- Main Method
- Statements
- Curly Braces
- Semicolons

General Structure

```java
public class ClassName {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        // Statements

    }

}
```

---

# Understanding Each Keyword

## public

An access modifier.

It allows the class or method to be accessed from anywhere.

---

## class

Used to define a class.

Every Java program belongs to a class.

---

## Main

Name of the class.

### Naming Rule

If the class is declared as public,

the file name must exactly match the class name.

Example

File Name

```
Main.java
```

Class

```java
public class Main
```

---

## public static void main(String[] args)

This is called the **main method**.

The JVM starts program execution from this method.

---

### public

Allows the JVM to access the method.

---

### static

Allows the JVM to call the method without creating an object.

---

### void

Indicates that the method does not return any value.

---

### main

Special method recognized by the JVM.

It is the entry point of every Java application.

---

### String[] args

Stores command-line arguments passed to the program.

We will study this in detail later.

---

# System.out.println()

Used to print output on the console.

Example

```java
System.out.println("Hello Java");
```

Output

```
Hello Java
```

---

# print() vs println()

## print()

Prints output on the same line.

Example

```java
System.out.print("Java ");
System.out.print("Spring");
```

Output

```
Java Spring
```

---

## println()

Prints output and moves the cursor to the next line.

Example

```java
System.out.println("Java");
System.out.println("Spring");
```

Output

```
Java
Spring
```

---

# Curly Braces

Curly braces `{}` define a block of code.

Example

```java
class Demo {

}
```

Everything inside belongs to the class.

---

# Semicolon (;)

Every Java statement ends with a semicolon.

Correct

```java
System.out.println("Hello");
```

Wrong

```java
System.out.println("Hello")
```

